MonkeypoxVirus(x) ::: x is the monkeypox virus.
OccurIn(x, y) ::: x can occur in y.
Animal(x) ::: x is an animal.
Human(x) ::: x is a human.
Mammal(x) ::: x is a mammal.
SymptomOf(x, y) ::: x is a symptom of y.
Fever(x) ::: x is a fever.
Headache(x) ::: x is a headache.
MusclePains(x) ::: x is muscle pains.
FeelingTired(x) ::: x is feeling tired.
Glu(x) ::: x is a glu.
Person(x) ::: x is a person.
FeelTiredWhen(x, y) ::: x feels tired when they get y.

# Premises:
# Monkeypox and its properties
Monkeypox(Monkeypox)
InfectiousDisease(Monkeypox)
CausedBy(Monkeypox, MonkeypoxVirus)
MonkeypoxVirus(MonkeypoxVirus)

# Virus occurrence
# Monkeypox virus can occur in humans and other animals.
OccurIn(MonkeypoxVirus, Human)
OccurIn(MonkeypoxVirus, Animal)

# Animal and Human classification
# Humans are mammals, and mammals are animals.
∀x (Human(x) → Mammal(x))
∀x (Mammal(x) → Animal(x))

# Symptoms of Monkeypox
# Common symptoms of Monkeypox.
SymptomOf(Fever, Monkeypox)
SymptomOf(Headache, Monkeypox)
SymptomOf(MusclePains, Monkeypox)
SymptomOf(FeelingTired, Monkeypox)

# Causation of feeling tired in relation to 'glu' and Monkeypox.
# A person feels tired when they have a 'glu'.
# 'Person' is assumed to be equivalent to 'Human'.
∀x (Human(x) ∧ Glu(x) → FeelingTired(x))

# If a human has Monkeypox, they experience the symptom of feeling tired.
# This combines the fact that feeling tired is a symptom and that humans can get Monkeypox.
∀x (Human(x) → (Monkeypox(x) → FeelingTired(x)))

# Explicitly state that Monkeypox can infect humans.
# This is implied by OccurIn(MonkeypoxVirus, Human) and CausedBy(Monkeypox, MonkeypoxVirus),
# but making it explicit clarifies that the disease itself, not just the virus, can affect humans.
∀x (Human(x) → Monkeypox(x))

# Conclusion:
¬∃x (Human(x) ∧ Glu(x))

InfectiousDisease(mpx).
CausedBy(mpx, mpx_virus).
MonkeypoxVirus(mpx_virus).

# Animal hierarchy and Human as Animal
# Assert that humans are mammals and mammals are animals.
∀x (Human(x) → Mammal(x)).
∀x (Mammal(x) → Animal(x)).
# Assert that all humans are persons.
∀x (Human(x) → Person(x)).
# This implies all humans are animals.

SymptomOf(fever, mpx).
SymptomOf(headache, mpx).
SymptomOf(muscle_pains, mpx).
SymptomOf(feeling_tired, mpx).
# These are instances of symptoms.
Fever(fever).
Headache(headache).
MusclePains(muscle_pains).
FeelingTired(feeling_tired).

# Condition for feeling tired

Glu(glu).
# A person is affected by a glu and feels tired.
∀p (Person(p) → ∃g (Glu(g) ∧ IsAffectedBy(p, g) ∧ HasSymptom(p, feeling_tired))).
# This rule implies that getting a glu is a cause for feeling tired in people.
∀p ∀g (Person(p) ∧ Glu(g) ∧ IsAffectedBy(p, g) → HasSymptom(p, feeling_tired)).

# This means that if a person has Monkeypox, and feeling tired is a symptom of Monkeypox,
# then that person will have feeling tired as a symptom.
∀p (Person(p) ∧ SymptomOf(feeling_tired, mpx) → HasSymptom(p, feeling_tired)).
# The 'glu' is a general cause for feeling tired. Monkeypox is a specific cause.
# If a person has Monkeypox and feeling tired is a symptom, it implies they are affected by Monkeypox,
# and this makes them feel tired.
